## Local Diff Analysis

A new **"Hello 👋"** welcome section has been added to README.md immediately after the repository description. This documentation change introduces new users to Silverforge's value proposition by explaining that the tool automates software engineering workflows by delegating coding tasks to Claude agents, running tests, performing code review, and opening PRs autonomously. The change is purely informational with no code impact, serving as improved onboarding and first-impression messaging. Placement is prominent and high in the README before detailed usage sections.

### Suggested Review Focus
- Accuracy of claims: The welcome section makes specific promises about functionality (delegates to Claude, runs tests, code review, opens PRs). Reviewers must verify these claims match implemented features and current capabilities in the codebase. False or aspirational claims could mislead users.
- Tone and audience alignment: The message targets both new users and decision-makers. Verify the friendly tone (emoji, conversational language) and technical specificity are appropriate for the intended audience and don't oversell or undersell features.
- Consistency with existing documentation: Check alignment with setup instructions, CLI commands, and architecture sections that follow. Verify the welcome section doesn't contradict or duplicate information in subsequent sections.
- Positioning and structure: The new section is inserted after the initial description line. Reviewers should assess whether this placement improves document flow and whether the README hierarchy remains logical.

### Trade-offs
- Documentation-code drift: welcome messaging may become outdated if features are added, removed, or modified without updating this section
- Specificity vs. flexibility: the detailed feature list (tests, code review, PR opening) binds documentation to current implementation—future pivots require updates
- Scope creep: a welcome section may invite feature requests or set expectations beyond current scope; monitor GitHub issues and user feedback

### Affected Modules
- Documentation (README.md) — user-facing onboarding and marketing content only

### Call Chain
- N/A — pure documentation change, no code execution paths affected

### Design Patterns
- README onboarding pattern — friendly welcome section to engage new visitors before technical details
- Value proposition statement — concise explanation of benefits (automated workflow, no manual work) before feature details

### Reviewer Checklist
- Verify all stated capabilities (Claude delegation, test running, code review, PR opening) are fully implemented and enabled in current version
- Check for typos, grammar, and emoji rendering across common platforms (GitHub, websites)
- Confirm tone matches brand voice and target audience (engineers, engineering managers, DevOps)
- Ensure this section doesn't duplicate or contradict the 'Two ways to use it' section that follows
- Review if claims like 'without any manual work in between' are realistic or require disclaimers (e.g., rate limits, eval phase failures)
- Consider if major features (Docker sandbox, eval commands, crucible/untangle phases, agent fallback) should be mentioned or are covered later
- Flag any forward-looking features marked as 'coming soon' vs. ready-now statements
- If this README is published to a website, verify the welcome section makes sense in that context too

