[agent-review] details:
Narrative:
This is a pure documentation change adding a welcome section to README.md. The change introduces a "Hello 👋" section that describes Silverforge's core functionality: delegating tasks to Claude, running tests, performing code review, and opening PRs. The review focuses on claim accuracy against implemented features, tone appropriateness, and consistency with existing documentation. Two key findings emerge: (1) an optimistic claim about "without any manual work in between" that could mislead users about failure scenarios, and (2) the phrase "with a single command" which oversimplifies the setup requirements slightly. Overall, the claims are substantially accurate but could be more precise about failure modes and prerequisites.

Findings:
- [Warning] README.md:7 Qualify the automation claim to acknowledge retry limits and potential failure scenarios. Users should understand that while the system automates the happy path, exhausted retries or eval failures may require manual debugging.
  description: The new welcome section claims the tool runs 'without any manual work in between.' This assumes the system always succeeds end-to-end. However, according to CLAUDE.md's architecture, the pipeline includes a retry loop that rebuilds prompts 'up to `max_iterations`' on blocking feedback. If max_iterations is exhausted or an unrecoverable error occurs (eval failure, evaluator rejection), manual intervention becomes necessary. The statement implies zero failure scenarios requiring user action, which is not guaranteed.
- [Info] README.md:7 No factual inaccuracies detected. All four claimed features are fully implemented and available in the codebase.
  description: The welcome section claims four capabilities: (1) 'delegating coding tasks to Claude' — verified in factory/coder.py and agent system; (2) 'running your tests' — verified via factory/evaluator.py running eval commands; (3) 'performing code review' — verified via factory/evaluator_agent.py and crucible phase; (4) 'opening PRs' — verified via factory/poller.py. All claims are accurate and backed by implemented features documented in the CLAUDE.md architecture section.
- [Info] README.md:7 The phrase 'single command' is accurate for the operational workflow but omits setup context. Users should be directed to the setup section immediately after this introduction to set proper expectations.
  description: The welcome section states 'Silverforge handles the entire pipeline with a single command.' While technically true for operation (factory run, factory poll), this claim omits important setup prerequisites: (1) 'factory setup' for one-time onboarding, (2) worker machine configuration (SSH, agents, tools), (3) .env variables (FACTORY_GITHUB_TOKEN, etc.). New users reading this might attempt to run the tool immediately without setup and encounter failures.
- [Info] README.md:5-10 Establish a maintenance guideline: any changes to factory/runner.py pipeline phases or key modules should trigger a review of this welcome section for accuracy. Consider adding a comment in the code linking to this README section for cross-reference.
  description: The new welcome section makes specific claims about implemented features (Claude agents, test running, code review, PR opening). If future versions modify, remove, or replace these phases (e.g., agent fallback to codex, removal of crucible phase, change to evaluator logic), this high-visibility section must be updated in parallel. There is currently no explicit maintenance process to keep this section synchronized with the architecture. This is a known trade-off from the review context.
- [Info] README.md:5-9 The emoji choice is appropriate for a README on GitHub. No action required unless the README is published to multiple formats (plaintext, PDF, website) where fallbacks would be needed.
  description: The welcome section header uses the 👋 emoji: '## Hello 👋'. GitHub renders emojis correctly, but this may cause issues in: (1) plaintext terminals or CI logs, (2) non-UTF-8 environments, (3) some markdown renderers that strip emoji. This is a very minor issue since most users will view README on GitHub.

